================================================================================
  CUDA Image Processing Pipeline — Installation Guide
================================================================================

PREREQUISITES
-------------
  1. NVIDIA GPU with Compute Capability >= 3.5
  2. CUDA Toolkit >= 11.0 (includes nvcc compiler)
  3. GNU Make (Linux/macOS) or MSYS2/WSL (Windows)
  4. GCC >= 7.0 or compatible C++ compiler

LINUX / WSL
-----------
  # Install CUDA Toolkit (Ubuntu/Debian)
  sudo apt update
  sudo apt install -y nvidia-cuda-toolkit

  # Verify installation
  nvcc --version
  nvidia-smi

  # Build
  make clean && make

  # Run
  ./run.sh
  # or: make run

GOOGLE COLAB (Recommended — no local GPU needed)
-------------------------------------------------
  1. Open a new Colab notebook at https://colab.research.google.com
  2. Go to Runtime > Change runtime type > GPU (T4)
  3. Upload src/gpu_image_processing.cu or paste it with %%writefile
  4. Run:
       !mkdir -p sample_output
       !nvcc -O2 -o imgpipeline gpu_image_processing.cu
       !./imgpipeline --num_images 200 --width 256 --height 256

WINDOWS (Native)
----------------
  1. Install CUDA Toolkit from https://developer.nvidia.com/cuda-downloads
  2. Open "x64 Native Tools Command Prompt" or Developer PowerShell
  3. Run: nvcc -O2 -o imgpipeline.exe src\gpu_image_processing.cu
  4. Run: imgpipeline.exe --num_images 200

VERIFYING GPU ACCESS
--------------------
  nvidia-smi          # Should list your GPU
  nvcc --version      # Should show CUDA compiler version

TROUBLESHOOTING
---------------
  - "nvcc not found": Add CUDA bin directory to PATH
    export PATH=/usr/local/cuda/bin:$PATH
  - "no CUDA-capable device": Ensure NVIDIA drivers are installed
  - Colab: Runtime > Change runtime type > select GPU
